definition.value: Any substance produced by linking glucuronic acid to another substance via a glycosidic bond.
A pentenedioic acid that is pent-2-ene substituted by carboxy groups at positions 1 and 5.
An indolyl carboxylate ester obtained by formal condensation of one of the primary hydroxy groups of D-arabinitol with the carboxy group of (2R)-2-(indol-3-yl)propanoic acid.
A  2-enoyl-CoA that is the glutaconyl derivative of CoA.
An  aldehydic acid derived from the  formal reduction of one of the carboxy groups glutamic acid to a formyl group.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of glutamic acid at the amino group or either of the carboxy groups, or from the replacement of any hydrogen by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing glutamic acid residues.

A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-glutamine at the amino group, the carboxy group, or the carboxamide, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-glutamine by a heteroatom.
An L-alpha-amino acid which is L-glutamic acid or any of the essential amino acids biosynthesised from it (glutamine, proline and arginine). A closed class.
An EC 6.3.* (C-N bond-forming ligase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of glutamate--ammonia ligase (EC 6.3.1.2).
A dipeptide in which one of the amino acid residues is glutamine.
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide that is formally derived from glutaric acid by conversion of one of the two carboxylic acid groups to the corresponding amide.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of glutaric acid.
A quinolizidine alkaloid that is lycopodine having a C=C double bond at the 11-position, a keto substituent at the 8-position and the keto group at position 5 replaced by a beta-hydroxy group.
Any  omega-carboxyacyl-CoA in which the acyl group specified is glutaryl or its substituted derivative.
Any bioconjugate in which glutathione is one of the components
Any organonitrogen compound derived from the Glu-Cys-Gly tripeptide glutathione.
A monophosphoglyceric acid having the phospho group at the 2-position.
An aldonic acid phosphate where the aldonic acid component is glyceric acid.
An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is 3H-furo[2,3-b]pyrano[3,2-f]quinoline carrying a gem-dimethyl group at position 3 as well as two methoxy substituents at positions 5 and 11.
Any ether having glyceryl as at least one of the O-substituents.
A quinoline alkaloid that is furo[2,3-b]quinoline bearing four methoxy substituents at positions 4, 5, 7 and 8.
An alkaloid antineoplastic agent isolated from Acronychia baueri.
A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of glycine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of glycine by a heteroatom.
A quinoline alkaloid that is furo[2,3-b]quinolin-4-one bearing additional 3,3-dimethylallyl and methoxy substituents at positions 9 and 7 respectively.
An aldehyde derived from a glycol by reduction of one of the hydroxy groups.
